# ianua-mind — Backend Conventions (Flask)

## Stack
- Python 3.12+ / Flask / ianua-library (`ianuacare`) / Docker

## Architecture
- API-first backend: business logic in services/modules, thin Flask routes
- Prefer package layout by domain (`app/<domain>/...`) over generic util dumping
- Keep handlers/controllers focused on: parse input, call service, map output/errors

## Flask Patterns
- Create app via factory (`create_app`) and register blueprints by module
- Validate request payloads explicitly (schema-based when available)
- Return structured JSON errors with stable error codes
- Never put domain logic directly in blueprint functions

## ianua-library Integration
- Use `ianuacare` as domain dependency, wrapped by local adapter/services
- Avoid scattering direct library calls across endpoints
- Convert library exceptions to app-level typed errors before responding
- Pin/track library updates in `requirements.txt` and test impacted flows

## Configuration
- Use environment variables for runtime configuration
- Never hardcode secrets or tokens in source code
- Keep defaults safe and production-oriented (explicit debug toggles)

## API Design
- Version endpoints (`/api/v1/...`) for new APIs
- Keep response shape consistent: `data`, `meta`, `errors` (when relevant)
- Include request correlation id in logs and error payloads when available

## Quality Gates
- Tests: `pytest`
- Lint/format: `ruff` (+ `black` if enabled by project)
- Type checking: `mypy` for critical modules and service boundaries
